Summary of Visual Changes
Now I have a complete picture of the editions table. Let me provide a comprehensive design review and improvement recommendations.
Editions Table Design Review
Current State Analysis
The table is functionally solid with good features (inline editing, expandable rows, bulk actions, pagination), but visually it feels like a standard enterprise data table rather than a tool befitting an art gallery inventory system.
Aesthetic Direction: "Gallery Curator's Desk"
Given the existing coastal aesthetic with serif typography and sandy/ocean tones, I recommend evolving toward a refined gallery documentation aesthetic — think museum inventory cards, exhibition catalogs, and archival records. Clean, elegant, yet highly functional.
Key Improvements
1. Table Container & Headers
Current: Plain white box with generic gray borders Proposed: Subtle elevation with refined borders, header that feels like archival tabs

┌─ Edition ─┬─ Artwork ─┬─ Size ─┬─ Location ─┬─ Price ─┬─ Status ─┐
│  #4/350   │ Bembridge │ Large  │ Purbeck    │  £450   │    ●     │
Add a subtle left accent border on the container (using the accent color)
Header row with slightly warmer background and refined typography
Sticky header on scroll with a soft shadow reveal
2. Status Indicators — Visual Revolution
Replace dropdown selects with visual status chips that are immediately scannable: Printing Status:
○ Empty circle = Not Printed (gray)
● Filled circle = Printed (ocean blue)
Sale Status:
◇ Diamond outline = Available (neutral)
◆ Filled diamond = Sold (seafoam)
✓ Checkmark = Settled (gold)
This allows at-a-glance scanning of 50+ rows instantly.
3. Row Hover & Selection States
Current: Generic gray hover, blue selection Proposed:
Hover: Subtle warm sand tint + left accent reveal
Selected: Soft blue-gray with checkmark indicator
Active row glow when editing
4. Inline Editing UX Improvements
Current: Click to edit, input appears Proposed:
Pencil icon hint on hover (subtle, right-aligned)
Double-click to edit (single click for navigation)
Inline validation with soft red/green border feedback
Success checkmark animation on save
5. Expandable Row — "Exhibition Card"
Current: Gray background panel with dense text Proposed: Transform into an exhibition documentation card:
Left accent border (using coastal palette)
Section dividers with subtle horizontal rules
Key-value layout with elegant spacing
Notes section styled like curatorial annotations
6. Pagination — Refined Controls
Current: Standard button row Proposed:
"Showing 1-50 of 7,879" with elegant typography
Compact page selector (no numbered buttons, just prev/next + direct input)
Optional: "Jump to edition" quick search
7. Bulk Action Bar — Contextual Actions
Current: Blue banner with button row Proposed:
Slide-up animation from bottom
Icon-based actions with labels on hover
Count displayed with subtle animation
Undo option for recent actions
Color Refinements for Status
Leverage the existing coastal palette:

/* Status Palette */
--status-sold: var(--seafoam);      /* Emerald teal - completed sale */
--status-printed: var(--accent);     /* Ocean blue - ready inventory */
--status-pending: var(--coral);      /* Sunset orange - needs attention */
--status-settled: var(--gold);       /* Sandy gold - fully resolved */
--status-available: var(--muted-foreground); /* Neutral */
Implementation Priority
Priority	Change	Impact
High	Status indicator redesign (circles/diamonds)	Immediate scannability
High	Row hover/selection states	Better interaction feedback
Medium	Expandable row styling	Consistent aesthetic
Medium	Inline edit affordances	Clearer UX patterns
Low	Pagination refinement	Minor polish
Low	Bulk action animation	Delight factor
Would you like me to implement these improvements? I can start with the highest-impact changes (status indicators and row styling) and work down from there.